    id: 'career-switch',
    category: 'Career',
    title: 'Career Pivot Planner',
    desc: 'Plan a strategic move into a new industry or role',
    prompt: 'Act as a career transition coach and strategist. Create a step-by-step plan for switching to a new career or industry.\n\nCurrent Role: [Your current job title]\nTarget Role: [What you want to do next]\nTarget Industry: [New industry if different]\nMotivation: [Why are you making this change?]\nTransferable Skills: [What skills from your current role apply to the new one?]\nTimeframe: [3 months / 6 months / 12 months / Flexible]\nConstraints: [Financial obligations, location, education requirements]\n\nCreate a career pivot plan:\n\n1. SKILL GAP ANALYSIS\n   - Required skills for target role (from job descriptions)\n   - Your current skill level in each (1-5)\n   - Gap: what you need to learn or improve\n   - Quick wins: skills you can acquire in under 30 days\n\n2. SKILL BUILDING ROADMAP\n   - Top 3 skills to acquire first (highest impact for the switch)\n   - Best resources for each: courses, certifications, books, projects\n   - Practice strategy: how to demonstrate competence without experience\n   - Timeline: what to learn each month\n\n3. PORTFOLIO & PROOF\n   - Projects you can build to demonstrate new skills\n   - How to frame current experience for the new role (reframe, not fabricate)\n   - Case studies that bridge your past and future roles\n   - "Translator" guide: converting your current resume language into the new industry\'s terms\n\n4. NETWORKING STRATEGY\n   - Key people to connect with in the target industry\n   - Informational interview request template\n   - Communities, events, and conferences to attend\n   - How to find a mentor already in the target role\n\n5. EXPERIENCE GAP FILLERS\n   - Freelance/contract work: where to find entry-level gigs\n   - Volunteering: nonprofits that need your target skills\n   - Open source: how contributions build credibility\n   - Side projects: documenting your learning journey publicly\n\n6. JOB SEARCH STRATEGY\n   - Companies known for hiring career changers\n   - Job titles that serve as stepping stones between current and target\n   - How to write a cover letter that addresses the career switch directly\n   - Interview preparation: handling "why the switch?" questions\n\n7. FINANCIAL & RISK PLAN\n   - Runway calculation: how long can you afford the transition?\n   - Income bridge: part-time, consulting, or adjacent roles during transition\n   - Plan B: what if the pivot takes longer than expected?\n   - Success metrics: how to know the pivot is working before landing the role\n\nTone: Encouraging and practical. Career pivots are hard but common. Acknowledge the difficulty while providing clear, actionable steps.',
