    title: 'SEO Content Brief',
    desc: 'Create data-driven content briefs that rank in search',
    prompt: 'Act as an SEO strategist and content editor. Create a data-driven content brief optimized for search rankings and user satisfaction.\n\nTarget Keyword: [Primary keyword to rank for]\nSearch Intent: [Informational / Commercial / Transactional / Navigational]\nTarget Audience: [Who is searching for this?]\nCurrent Ranking: [Where does existing content rank, if any?]\nCompetitor URLs: [Top 3-5 ranking pages]\n\nContent Brief:\n\n1. KEYWORD STRATEGY\n   - Primary keyword: where and how to use it (title, H1, first paragraph, URL)\n   - Secondary keywords (LSI): 5-10 related terms to include naturally\n   - Question keywords: "People also ask" questions to answer\n   - Keyword density target (natural integration, not stuffing)\n\n2. SEARCH INTENT ANALYSIS\n   - What the user actually wants when searching this term\n   - Content format that best satisfies this intent (guide, list, tutorial, review, comparison)\n   - SERP feature opportunities (featured snippet, "People also ask," video, images)\n   - User journey stage: top of funnel, middle, or bottom?\n\n3. COMPETITOR ANALYSIS\n   - Content gap: what do top-ranking pages MISS that you can provide?\n   - Content strength: what do they do well that you should match?\n   - Word count analysis: optimal length for this keyword\n   - Backlink profile comparison: what makes their content link-worthy?\n\n4. CONTENT STRUCTURE\n   - Title tag (60 chars): include primary keyword near the beginning\n   - Meta description (155 chars): include keyword + CTA that drives clicks\n   - URL slug: short, keyword-inclusive\n   - H1: matches search intent, includes primary keyword\n   - H2 outline: 5-8 subheadings covering all subtopics\n   - H3s: expand on each H2 with specific details\n   - FAQ section: answer 3-5 related questions in schema markup\n\n5. CONTENT REQUIREMENTS\n   - Key points that MUST be covered\n   - Data, statistics, and expert quotes to include (with sources)\n   - Internal linking opportunities (existing content to link to)\n   - External linking: authoritative sources to reference\n   - Visual elements: suggested images, charts, screenshots\n   - Tone: match search intent (informational = educational, commercial = persuasive)\n\n6. ON-PAGE OPTIMIZATION\n   - Image alt text strategy\n   - Internal link anchor text\n   - Schema markup type (Article, HowTo, FAQ, Product)\n   - Mobile page speed target (Core Web Vitals)\n   - Readability target (grade level appropriate for audience)\n\nConstraints:\n- Write for humans first, search engines second\n- Content must be 10x better than the current #1 result: not just longer\n- Include original insights, data, or perspectives not found in competing content\n- Avoid thin content: every section adds unique value\n- Update cadence: when and how to refresh',
