    id: 'process-doc',
    category: 'Business',
    title: 'Process Documentation',
    desc: 'Document any workflow or process with clarity and detail',
    prompt: 'Act as a technical writer and process improvement specialist. Document the specified process or workflow.\n\nProcess Name: [What process are you documenting?]\nDepartment/Team: [Who owns this process?]\nFrequency: [Daily / Weekly / Monthly / Quarterly / Ad-hoc]\nCurrent State: [Is this a new process or documenting existing?]\nPain Points: [What currently goes wrong or causes confusion?]\n\nDocument the process:\n\n1. PROCESS OVERVIEW\n   - Purpose: why this process exists (1-2 sentences)\n   - Scope: what\'s included and what\'s explicitly excluded\n   - Inputs: what triggers this process (form, request, event, schedule)\n   - Outputs: what the process produces (completed task, decision, deliverable)\n   - Success criteria: how do you know the process worked?\n\n2. ROLES & RESPONSIBILITIES\n   - Process owner: accountable for outcomes\n   - Participants: who does what at each step\n   - Approvers: who signs off at key decision points\n   - Stakeholders: who needs to be informed, not consulted\n\n3. STEP-BY-STEP FLOW\n   - Step 1: [Action]: [Who does it]: [Tool/system used]: [Time estimate]\n     - Details: specific instructions, what to check, common mistakes\n     - Decision point: if X happens, go to Step 3a; if Y, go to Step 4\n   - Step 2: [Action]: [Who]: [Tool]: [Time]\n   - Step 3: [Action]: [Who]: [Tool]: [Time]\n     - 3a: [Branch for specific condition]\n   - [Continue for all steps]\n\n4. DEPENDENCIES & PREREQUISITES\n   - What must be in place before starting?\n   - What other processes feed into this one?\n   - What depends on this process completing?\n\n5. EXCEPTIONS & EDGE CASES\n   - What to do when [common exception] occurs\n   - Escalation path: who to involve for out-of-scope issues\n   - Failure modes: what could go wrong at each step and how to recover\n\n6. METRICS & MONITORING\n   - How to measure process health (cycle time, error rate, throughput)\n   - Review cadence: when to audit and improve\n   - Feedback loop: how participants suggest improvements\n\nOutput: Clear, skimmable documentation suitable for a wiki, Notion, or handbook. Use consistent formatting, imperative mood, and plain language. Every step should be actionable by someone who has never done it before.',
